  By last March, the father
was impressed enough to put
up $100 and enter Dominick
in the annual pool. The fa-
ther also entered himself,
and the two of them sat down
together at the kitchen table
to fill their respective sheets.
  The father mixed favorites
with underdogs for the vari-
ous rounds of the NCAA
championships. He chose
Florida to take the title.
  "I thought they could go all
the way," John says.
  Dominick decided that the
championship would come
down to Duke versus Arkan-
sas. He foresaw that Arkan-
sas would win.
  "They looked like they
were playing the best," Domi-
nick says.
  The sheets were submitted
to those running the pool,
and over the days ahead
Dominick returned home
from first grade to learn he
had picked right again. The
end of the second round saw
him doing so well that two
men called C & S to offer
$1,000 for his sheet. The fa-
ther relayed the offer to his
son. Dominick had an imme-
diate answer.
  "He said, `No, I want to
win,' " John remembers.
